  "prompt": "What function do sclerenchyma cells serve?",
  "response": "Sclerenchyma cells are a type of plant cell that primarily serve to provide structural support and strength to various parts of the plant. They have thick, lignified cell walls, which makes them rigid and durable. Sclerenchyma cells can be found in different forms, such as fibers, which are elongated and help reinforce the plant, and sclereids, which are shorter and contribute to the hardness of certain plant parts, like seeds and nut shells.\n\nIn summary, the main functions of sclerenchyma cells include:\n\n1. **Support**: They help maintain the shape of the plant and withstand various stresses, such as wind or weight.\n2. **Protection**: They protect softer tissues and organs by providing a hard outer layer.\n3. **Strength**: Their lignified walls contribute to the overall mechanical strength of the plant.\n\nOverall, sclerenchyma cells are crucial for the structural integrity and durability of plants.",
